# act — local GitHub Actions runner.
# https://github.com/nektos/act
#
# Why this file: pins the runner image to a known good ubuntu-latest
# variant so local runs match GitHub's hosted runners byte-for-byte.
# Without this, act defaults to `node:16-buster-slim` which is missing
# half of what GitHub provides (sudo, apt, pre-installed actions).
#
# Image sizes (downloaded once, cached forever):
#   micro:  ~200 MB  — node only, fails most workflows
#   medium: ~500 MB  — node + common runtimes, fine for typecheck/test
#   large:  ~20 GB   — full GitHub-hosted parity, slow first pull
#                       (only needed for native-release, not for `Tests`)
#
# Default to medium so the daily `pnpm act:test` is fast.
-P ubuntu-latest=catthehacker/ubuntu:act-latest

# Pull policy: never re-pull images that are already local. Speeds up
# repeat runs; bump explicitly with `act --pull` when an image upgrade
# is needed.
--pull=false

# Reuse the same container between runs so the apt cache + pnpm store
# from the previous run survives. Trade-off: leaks state between runs.
# Disable per-run with `--rm` when you need a clean slate.
--reuse

# Use the local docker socket instead of starting docker-in-docker.
--container-daemon-socket -

# Load the .env.act file as workflow env (if it exists). Lets us pass
# BETTER_AUTH_SECRET / mock APPLE_API_KEY / etc. locally without
# polluting the shell. .env.act is gitignored.
--env-file .env.act

# Default to the M-series Apple Silicon build of the runner image so
# the container's architecture matches the host (no rosetta translation
# overhead). x86_64 hosts: comment this out, act auto-detects.
--container-architecture linux/amd64
